              "species": {
                "id": "419344a6-2a6e-5e60-9d47-352546eb5180",
                "description": "When it comes to food, fish crows are not picky and will eat just about anything. If there is anything left over, they will cache the surplus for later and use it to feed their young. Pairs are affectionate and often preen the back of each other's heads, but they can be quite the troublemakers when dealing with other birds. They have been known to harass them and steal food, as well as raid nests.",
                "name": "Northern Cardinal",
                "iconUrl": "https://media.example/.../THUMBNAIL.jpg",
                "__typename": "SpeciesBird"
              },
              "__typename": "CollectionSpecies"
            },
            {
              "isCollected": false,
              "media": null,
              "species": {
                "id": "a59ffb2c-0ab6-5af5-a62a-d84d15ee3fee",
                "description": "When the cows come home, so do brown-headed cowbirds; they get their name from following around grazing livestock that bring a lot of insects for them to eat. Work smart, not hard, right? That seems to apply to their parenting style as well or lack thereof. They are notorious nest parasites, laying eggs in the nests of other birds. When the baby cowbird hatches, it will roll the other eggs out of the nest!",
                "name": "Northern Cardinal",
                "iconUrl": "https://media.example/.../THUMBNAIL.jpg",
                "__typename": "SpeciesBird"
              },
              "__typename": "CollectionSpecies"
            },
            {
              "isCollected": false,
              "media": null,
              "species": {
                "id": "c1b50ccd-8122-5e15-a3e5-0d933669294b",
                "description": "There's no family like a crow family! A crow family is composed of around 15 crows and up to five different generations of young. Young crows help out with family duties before they start breeding between the ages of two and four. They are also very smart! They know how to make and use tools and know to follow other animals to find and steal their food.",
                "name": "Northern Cardinal",
                "iconUrl": "https://media.example/.../THUMBNAIL.jpg",
                "__typename": "SpeciesBird"
              },
              "__typename": "CollectionSpecies"
            },
            {
              "isCollected": false,
              "media": null,
              "species": {
                "id": "be613402-613f-5a51-aba0-fb0a989c98e7",
                "description": "These noisy birds will come to your feeders but usually eat from the ground and sometimes maybe even steal food right from under other birds' beaks! They engage in a practice called anting \u2013 this means they allow ants to walk all over their body and secrete formic acid, which is thought to kill parasites. Ants aren't their only means of pest control, though, they also use walnut juice, mothballs, lemons, limes and chokecherries.",
                "name": "Northern Cardinal",
                "iconUrl": "https://media.example/.../THUMBNAIL.jpg",
                "__typename": "SpeciesBird"
              },
              "__typename": "CollectionSpecies"
            },
            {
              "isCollected": true,
